To obtain the similar correction term for $\mathrm{C}_{2}$, defined as $\mathrm{DV}_{\mathrm{e} 2}$, the model in Fig. 17.12(b) is employed. Here, the switch procedure involves keeping the $b_{1}$ switch grounded while the comparator is reset, grounding the $b_{2}$ switch, and connecting the remaining switches $b_{3-N}, s_{N}$ to $\mathrm{V}_{\text {ref }}$. Next, the $b_{2}$ and $b_{3-N}, s_{N}$ switches are reversed (i.e., $b_{2}$ set to $\mathrm{V}_{\text {ref }}$ and the others grounded). Note that even if $\Delta \mathrm{C}_{2}$ is zero, the measured $V_{x}$ will be equivalent to $-D V_{e 1}$, since $-\Delta \mathrm{C}_{1}$ is assumed to be part of $\mathrm{C}_{3, \mathrm{NB}}$. Therefore, the error voltage due solely to $\mathrm{C}_{2}$ can be calculated by digitizing $V_{x}$, as before, but then subtracting $D V_{e 1}$ using digital circuitry. Mathematically,

$$
